</div>
<p>
so the covariance is zero. However, if the variables are correlated in some=
 way, then their covariance will be <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/Nonzero.html">nonzero</a>. In fact, if <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolf=
ram.com/images/equations/Covariance/Inline12.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" s=
tyle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"105" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"cov(X,Y)&gt;0">, then <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.=
com/images/equations/Covariance/Inline13.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21"=
 alt=3D"Y"> tends to increase as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
images/equations/Covariance/Inline14.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"=
max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"X"> increases, and if <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/=
equations/Covariance/Inline15.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"105" height=3D"21" alt=3D"co=
v(X,Y)&lt;0">, then <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equati=
ons/Covariance/Inline16.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:10=
0%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"Y"> tends=
 to decrease as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
Covariance/Inline17.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X"> increases=
. Note that while statistically independent variables
 are always uncorrelated, the converse is not necessarily true.
</p>
<p>
In the special case of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equ=
ations/Covariance/Inline18.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height=
